{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-06-14T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Layered ridges stretch across Badlands National Park in South Dakota. Their bands of pink, grey and gold shift with the light as eroded peaks and valleys come into view. Wind and water continue to shape this terrain, steadily wearing away soft sedimentary rock and exposing millions of years of Earth's history in layers formed by ancient rivers, volcanic ash and periods when shallow seas covered the region.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_ROW3111301246_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.BadSunset_ROW3111301246_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Sunset in Badlands National Park, South Dakota, United States","Copyright":"© Troy Harrison/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Badlands+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260613_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260613_BadSunset"},"Ssd":"20260613","Name":"BadSunset","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3111301246","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 13 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A streak of colour glides past a blur of wildflowers as a European bee-eater cuts through the air. Turquoise, gold and chestnut shimmer across its wings as it hunts in flight, snatching insects mid-air with swift turns. Bees and wasps are among its favoured prey, and the bird often removes the stinger before feeding—a behaviour that reduces the risk of injury.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_ROW2830964378_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpainBeeEater_ROW2830964378_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"European bee-eater in Sierra de Grazalema Natural Park, Cádiz, Spain","Copyright":"© Andres M. Dominguez/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=European+bee-eater&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260612_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260612_SpainBeeEater"},"Ssd":"20260612","Name":"SpainBeeEater","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2830964378","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 12 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Tucked away beneath steep cliffs near Cabo da Roca, the westernmost point of mainland Europe, Praia da Ursa feels like the edge of the continent. Reached by a narrow, rugged trail, this secluded beach along Portugal's Atlantic coast is shaped largely by wind, stone and powerful waves. When the tide recedes, the shoreline briefly widens. Smooth rocks emerge, and with them, small signs of life. Limpets cling tightly to the exposed stone, holding fast where the ocean usually breaks.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_ROW2196437468_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Limpets_ROW2196437468_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Limpets exposed at low tide on the coast of Praia da Ursa, Portugal","Copyright":"© Theo Bosboom/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260611_Limpets\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Praia+da+Ursa+Portugal&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260611_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260611_Limpets"},"Ssd":"20260611","Name":"Limpets","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2196437468","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 11 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"From above, the lake's smooth surface contrasts sharply with the rugged ground surrounding it. Hnausapollur crater lake—also known as Bláhylur—lies in the heart of Fjallabak Nature Reserve, a remote area of Iceland's highlands shaped more by volcanic activity than by human settlement. The crater formed when magma met groundwater, triggering an explosion that carved out the circular basin visible today.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_ROW9570499097_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Hnausapollur_ROW9570499097_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Hnausapollur volcanic crater lake, Fjallabak Nature Reserve, Landmannalaugar, Iceland","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hnausapollur+Iceland&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260610_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260610_Hnausapollur"},"Ssd":"20260610","Name":"Hnausapollur","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9570499097","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 10 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Vernazza is a small seaside town in Cinque Terre, in Italy's Liguria region. Built around the area's only natural harbour, it has long been tied to the sea. First recorded in 1080 as a fortified settlement and maritime base, it later became part of the Republic of Genoa's coastal defences. To this day, the village preserves its past in the ruins of Doria Castle and the watchtowers overlooking the bay. At the water's edge stands the Church of Santa Margherita d'Antiochia, first mentioned in 1318 and expanded in later centuries, with a bell tower overlooking the port. Above the houses and narrow lanes, steep terraces support vineyards and olive groves, shaped by generations of stonework in a landscape protected within Cinque Terre National Park, part of a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Picture an aperitivo here: a glass of local white wine, the harbour in view and Ligurian favourites like focaccia and basil pesto—basically a postcard you can taste.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_ROW6038252808_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CTNPVernazza_ROW6038252808_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Vernazza, Cinque Terre, Liguria, Italy","Copyright":"© Kelly Cheng/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Vernazza+Cinque+Terre+Liguria+Italy&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260609_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260609_CTNPVernazza"},"Ssd":"20260609","Name":"CTNPVernazza","Market":"ROW","Hash":"6038252808","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 9 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today, let's follow the lead of a creature that goes wherever the water takes it. Want to spot a lion's mane jellyfish? Look in cold northern seas. Its bell is divided into eight lobes, and beneath it trail long tentacles and oral arms that can capture plankton, fish and even other jellyfish. Well, a single animal may carry thousands of stinging cells on each tentacle. For humans, the sting can be painful, and even detached tentacles washed ashore may still react on contact. The rule is simple: admire it, then leave it alone.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_ROW5915372220_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Cyanea_ROW5915372220_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lion's mane jellyfish swimming in the ocean","Copyright":"© Alexander Semenov Images/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lions+mane+jellyfish&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260608_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260608_Cyanea"},"Ssd":"20260608","Name":"Cyanea","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5915372220","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 8 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At Dunseverick Castle in Northern Ireland, history hangs on—literally. Wall fragments cling to a basalt stack above the Atlantic, proving that even ruins can hold their ground. Two thousand years ago, it marked the end of the Slige Midluachra, one of Ireland's five great roads, linking travellers to the royal seat at Hill of Tara. In the 5th century, Saint Patrick is said to have visited and baptised a local man, Olcán, here. Tradition holds that the Lia Fáil (Stone of Destiny), used for crowning Irish kings, was taken from this shore for Scotland.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DunseverickCastle2026_ROW5774172338_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DunseverickCastle2026_ROW5774172338_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Ruins of Dunseverick Castle, County Antrim, Northern Ireland","Copyright":"© Krzysztof Rogalski/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260607_DunseverickCastle2026\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Dunseverick+Castle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260607_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260607_DunseverickCastle2026"},"Ssd":"20260607","Name":"DunseverickCastle2026","Market":"ROW","Hash":"5774172338","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 7 日"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A sculpted arch of ice rises from the Southern Ocean along the Antarctic Peninsula, one of the fastest-warming regions on Earth. This formation began as compacted snow that turned into glacial ice over thousands of years. Eventually, part of a glacier or floating ice shelf fractured and broke free—a process known as calving—creating a drifting iceberg.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ArchedIceberg_ROW4666187976_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ArchedIceberg_ROW4666187976_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Arched iceberg floating off the western Antarctic Peninsula, Southern Ocean","Copyright":"© Steven Kazlowski/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260620_ArchedIceberg\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Iceberg&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260620_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260620_ArchedIceberg"},"Ssd":"20260620","Name":"ArchedIceberg","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4666187976","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 20 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Perched at the far edge of Piazza Bovio in Piombino, Tuscany, Italy, is the Piombino Lighthouse. Locally, it is known as 'Faro di Piombino' or 'La Rocchetta Lighthouse.' It overlooks the point where the Tuscan coast faces the island of Elba.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IsolaElba_ROW4135146629_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IsolaElba_ROW4135146629_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"La Rocchetta Lighthouse, Piombino, Tuscany, Italy","Copyright":"© StevanZZ/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260619_IsolaElba\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=La+Rocchetta+Lighthouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260619_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260619_IsolaElba"},"Ssd":"20260619","Name":"IsolaElba","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4135146629","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 19 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Set high above Cusco in Peru, Sacsayhuamán reveals the ambition of the Inca Empire in stone. Built in the 15th century, this vast complex once formed part of the sacred capital of the Incas. From above, the layout becomes clear: terraces, open plazas and the remains of towers forming a carefully planned citadel. The largest walls, built from enormous blocks, still stand strong today. Some stones rise more than 8.2 metres tall and were fitted together so precisely—without mortar—that the structure has endured centuries of earthquakes.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.Saqsaywaman_ROW9340385062_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.Saqsaywaman_ROW9340385062_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Aerial view of the ruins of Sacsayhuamán, Cusco, Peru","Copyright":"© Creative-Family/Getty Images Plus","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260618_Saqsaywaman\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sacsayhuaman+Cusco+Peru&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260618_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260618_Saqsaywaman"},"Ssd":"20260618","Name":"Saqsaywaman","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9340385062","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 18 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Follow the glowing ribbon of switchbacks and you'll find one of Switzerland's most legendary drives: Tremola Road, the historic southern approach to the Saint Gotthard Pass, above Airolo. Built in the early 1800s and largely shaped by a 1951 reconstruction, this route is celebrated as Switzerland's longest monument to historic road construction. Its showstopper stretch climbs about 299 metres in just 4 kilometres, curling through 24 named hairpin bends on granite cobblestones, with sturdy retaining walls edging the way. Overall, it runs about 11 kilometres and features 37 bends in total. Take it slow—every curve feels like a step back in time, trading speed for sweeping mountain scenery and big views toward the upper Leventina Valley. Whether you're driving, cycling or pulling over for photos, look for the Grand Tour of Switzerland photo spot framing those iconic zigzags.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TremolaRoad_ROW9264574129_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TremolaRoad_ROW9264574129_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Tremola Road on the Saint Gotthard Pass in Airolo, Switzerland","Copyright":"© Sandro Bisaro/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260617_TremolaRoad\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tremola+Road&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260617_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260617_TremolaRoad"},"Ssd":"20260617","Name":"TremolaRoad","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9264574129","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 17 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Sea turtles have been navigating Earth's oceans for more than 100 million years. Imagine crossing vast stretches of open water and returning to the same beach decades later. Long migrations between feeding and nesting grounds are central to their lives, with some travelling thousands of kilometres across the oceans. They also play an important role in marine ecosystems by maintaining seagrass beds and helping to keep coral reefs healthy. Despite their resilience, all sea turtle species face threats including habitat loss, plastic pollution, climate change and accidental capture in fishing gear.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SevenMileTurtle_ROW9119311274_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SevenMileTurtle_ROW9119311274_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Hawksbill sea turtle pair near Seven Mile Beach, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands","Copyright":"© Alex Mustard/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260616_SevenMileTurtle\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Hawksbill+sea+turtle&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260616_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260616_SevenMileTurtle"},"Ssd":"20260616","Name":"SevenMileTurtle","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9119311274","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 16 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"These mountains were shaped over time—and June 15, 1934, helped protect them. That's when the Great Smoky Mountains National Park was established in Tennessee and North Carolina. Covering over 2,112 square kilometres, the park takes its name from the natural smoky haze drifting over its ridgelines. Part of the Appalachian Mountains, these peaks are over 300 million years old.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_ROW8995340148_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParkEstd_ROW8995340148_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Great Smoky Mountains National Park, Tennessee, United States","Copyright":"© Mint Images/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Great+Smoky+Mountains+National+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260615_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260615_ParkEstd"},"Ssd":"20260615","Name":"ParkEstd","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8995340148","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 15 日"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At daybreak, the mallard glides over the still water like a brush across a canvas. Its shimmering plumage—emerald-green head in the male, speckled brown coat in the female—catches the first light. It can be seen from the marshes of the Camargue to the urban canals of Amsterdam, a faithful companion of Europe's aquatic landscapes.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DuckPond_ROW8945252603_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DuckPond_ROW8945252603_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Mallard duck","Copyright":"© Philippe Paternolli/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260614_DuckPond\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mallard+duck&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260614_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260614_DuckPond"},"Ssd":"20260614","Name":"DuckPond","Market":"ROW","Hash":"8945252603","FullDateString":"2026 年 6月 月 14 日"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"今日圖片","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"深入了解","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"立即捐贈","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"快速事實:","LOC_HOMEPAGE_GALLERY_CARD_TITLE":"最近的首頁圖片","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_GALLERY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"{0}的首頁圖片","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_TITLE":"在歷史上的這一天","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"在這一天的 {0}，{1}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_SHARE_TOOLTIP":"分享今日 Bing 首頁","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERDOWNLOAD_TOOLTIP":"下載此影像。禁止將此影像用於桌布以外的用途。","LOC_MUSCARD_DOWNLOAD_LINK":"下載這張圖片","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERNOTAVAILABLE":"此圖片無法下載作為桌布。","LOC_HOMEPAGE_INFO_TEXT":"資訊","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK":"https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2127455","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK_TEXT":"取得新的 Bing Wallpaper 應用程式","LOC_BING_